## Problem Statement *(Linh)*

Amazon's last-mile delivery network faces increasing pressure to deliver faster, more cheaply, more safely, and more sustainably while maintaining customer trust. Last-mile delivery is one of the most complex parts of logistics because it must balance customer promises, urban congestion, failed delivery attempts, driver safety, labor capacity, and high volumes of time-sensitive orders.

The business problem is that Amazon's current last-mile operations are exposed to avoidable delivery delays, inefficient routing, vehicle underutilization, data fragmentation, and safety and compliance failures that cannot be adequately mitigated without integrated, real-time AI-driven route optimization. From an ERM perspective, these operational inefficiencies represent compounding risks across people, processes, technology, and regulatory domains — each of which must be addressed as part of any acquisition decision.

