## Key Risk Indicators (KRIs) *(Linh)*

The table below presents Key Risk Indicators developed across the business's people, processes, technology, facilities, and other critical operational dimensions, reflecting both standard operational risks and the technical and information security risks specific to an AI-powered delivery optimization acquisition.

| **Risk Area** | **Sample KRI** | **Warning Threshold** | **ERM Relevance** |
|---|---|---|---|
| People | Driver/DSP adoption rate of AI route recommendations | Below 80% adoption for two consecutive months | Signals poor change management, weak training, or distrust of algorithmic decisions. |
| People | Driver safety incidents per 100,000 deliveries | Increase of 10% or more after rollout | Shows whether optimization pressure is harming safety or creating reputational risk. |
| Processes | On-time delivery rate | Falls below 95%, or declines by more than 3 percentage points vs. pre-integration baseline, for two consecutive periods | Directly measures whether the acquisition delivers on its core operational rationale. A declining on-time rate post-integration signals integration failure and triggers financial, reputational, and customer trust risk simultaneously. |
| Processes | Failed delivery/re-attempt rate | Increases above the 30-day pre-integration baseline by 5 percentage points or more for two consecutive months post-rollout | Sustained re-attempt increases drive cost overruns, customer satisfaction penalties, and reputational harm, and indicate that the AI routing data quality or address validation process is failing. |
| Technology | AI model uptime/availability | Below 99.5% monthly availability | Monitors resilience of the acquired service as a mission-critical delivery system. |
| Technology | Route recommendation error rate | More than 2% of routes require manual override due to a clear system error | Detects model drift, bad data inputs, or integration defects. |
| Information Security | High-severity vulnerabilities unresolved beyond SLA | Any critical vulnerability older than 15 days | Tracks the exposure of customer, driver, location, and operational data. |
| Information Security | Unauthorized access or anomalous API activity | Any confirmed unauthorized access event | Protects sensitive routing, customer address, and delivery proof data. |
| Facilities/Assets | Vehicle utilization rate | Falls below the target by more than 5% | Shows whether route optimization matches packages, vans, and drivers efficiently. |
| Facilities/Assets | Delivery station congestion or late dispatch percentage | More than 5% of routes dispatched late | Links physical facility readiness to AI planning reliability. |
| Compliance/Regulatory | Open regulatory, privacy, or AI governance findings | Any high-risk finding unresolved beyond 30 days; any CCPA or EU AI Act compliance gap without a remediation plan within 14 days | Unresolved regulatory findings expose Amazon to enforcement penalties, antitrust investigation, and reputational harm. |
| Technology – AI/Algorithm | Delivery outcome disparity by geography or demographic zone (algorithmic bias indicator) | Statistically significant on-time gap (>5%) between highest- and lowest-performing zones, persisting 60+ days post-rollout | Systemic delivery disparities tied to AI routing create legal liability and directly expose Amazon to EU AI Act algorithmic accountability requirements. |
| Processes – Data Quality | AI model input data quality score | Input score falls below 95% in any market for two consecutive weeks; or any critical data feed (address, traffic, scan timestamp) reports completeness below 90% | AI model output is only as reliable as its inputs. Poor data quality is a leading indicator of model drift and cascading delivery failures. |

